;; Book of Narrative Games — Chapter 3: What You Did Before

(dialect :applies ("motoi" "sakura"))

(chapter
  :book                "Book of Narrative Games"
  :chapter-number      3
  :title               "What You Did Before"
  :dialect             "motoi"
  :audience            :kid
  :also-for            :adult
  :content-rating      :G
  :author-lane         "narrative-games-engineer-lane-2026-07-16"
  :training-eligible   #t
  :confidentiality     "public"
  :voice               "sakura-teaching + narrative-craft"
  :book-version        "1.0.0"
  :draws-from-preserved (:book "book-of-games-preserved" :ch 2)
  :prose
"The trick of a good narrative game is that the story remembers. Not the
kid. The story. She made a choice thirty minutes ago and she has
forgotten it, and then a character three rooms later says 'I heard
about what you did with the fox.' She gets goosebumps. That is not a
literary effect. That is code.

The code is a key-value store called Cortex that survives every kind of
break — the frame ending, the game closing, the phone going to sleep,
the kid coming back tomorrow. Anything you write to Cortex is still
there when she opens the game again. That means the character you built
last night still knows what she did.

This chapter is about using Cortex well. Not just writing to it. Using
it — reading it at the right moments, tagging it with the right keys,
letting it accumulate into a shape that feels like a person's memory
of a person.

---

## 3.1 The three verbs

You will use three Cortex verbs for the whole book.

```scheme
(cortex/write key value)      ;; remember this
(cortex/read key)             ;; what did you remember?
(cortex/topk n)               ;; the n most recent things you remembered
```

`cortex/write 'saved-the-fox #t` stores the boolean #t under the key
`saved-the-fox`. That's it. Any Motoi Scheme value works: a symbol,
a number, a string, a list, a nested list. Write anything you want to
be able to look up later.

`cortex/read 'saved-the-fox` returns #t if we wrote it, or #f if we
never touched that key. Simple lookup. If you want a default when the
key is missing, use `(or (cortex/read 'saved-the-fox) #f)`.

`cortex/topk 5` returns the five most recently written entries, newest
first. This is how you build a 'previously on…' recap without keeping
your own log. Cortex keeps a log for you.

Those three verbs are 95% of narrative-game memory. Everything else in
this chapter is patterns for using them.

---

## 3.2 The keys have a shape

Do not just scatter keys named `x`, `y`, `flag1`. Give them namespaces.
Future you needs to know what a key means when she reads it in scene 40.

```scheme
;; A good key naming scheme:
;;
;;  'state/*        — world flags: 'state/door-unlocked, 'state/well-poisoned
;;  'inventory      — the kid's stuff (a list)
;;  'past-choices   — an alist of important choices made
;;  'reputation/*   — how NPCs feel: 'reputation/mira, 'reputation/villain
;;  'seen/*         — which scenes have been visited
;;  'save/slot/1    — full snapshot bundles
;;
;; So instead of:
(cortex/write 'red #t)

;; do:
(cortex/write 'state/first-door-red? #t)

;; And instead of:
(cortex/write 'inv (cons 'lantern (cortex/read 'inv)))

;; do:
(cortex/write 'inventory (cons 'lantern (or (cortex/read 'inventory) '())))
```

The namespace tells you the meaning. When you are debugging a game a
month from now and you see `'state/well-poisoned` in a log, you know
exactly what it does. Appendix A tabulates the full recommended
namespace.

The `or` idiom — `(or (cortex/read 'inventory) '())` — is the safe way
to append. If inventory has never been touched, `cortex/read` returns
#f, and #f cannot be `cons`ed onto. We coerce to the empty list first,
then cons. Do this every time you extend a list-shaped Cortex key.

---

## 3.3 The shopkeeper who remembers

Here is the game we have been building toward. The kid played the
kitchen last night, took the red door, ate the honey. Today she
continues the story. She walks into a shop.

```scheme
;; The shop scene reads Cortex and greets the kid personally.
(define (shop-scene)
  (scene/imagine)
  (surface/paper)
  (let ((first-choice (cortex/read 'state/first-choice))
        (ate-honey?   (cortex/read 'state/ate-the-honey))
        (has-tomato?  (member 'tomato (or (cortex/read 'inventory) '()))))
    (paint-text 20 40 (shopkeeper-greeting first-choice ate-honey? has-tomato?))
    (paint-text 20 200 \"[A] buy something   [B] tell her about the note\")
    (on-key
      (lambda (k)
        (case k
          ((a) (shop-catalog))
          ((b) (tell-about-note))))))
  (paint-text 20 250 \"[Q] leave the shop\"))

(define (shopkeeper-greeting first-choice ate-honey? has-tomato?)
  (cond
    ((and (eq? first-choice 'garden) has-tomato?)
     \"Oh — Mira said you might come. She could smell tomato on you\nfrom the porch. Sit, sit.\")
    ((eq? first-choice 'garden)
     \"You are the one who came through the garden. Mira told me.\")
    ((and (eq? first-choice 'hall) ate-honey?)
     \"You are the one who ate the honey. It shows around your mouth.\nDo not worry, I laugh, come in.\")
    ((eq? first-choice 'hall)
     \"You are the one who came through the hall. The cat is mine, by\nthe way. She likes you.\")
    (else
     \"Welcome. I do not think we have met.\")))
```

Five possible greetings based on what the kid did last night. The kid
took the garden door AND has a tomato — the shopkeeper knows Mira told
her, and can smell the tomato. The kid took the hall AND ate the honey
— the shopkeeper is amused, notes the honey around her mouth.
Otherwise, the shopkeeper is polite but no history to draw on.

This is the moment the kid feels seen. She did not tell the shopkeeper
anything. The game did. The game had its ear pressed to the door.

If the shopkeeper mentioned facts the kid does NOT recognize — 'you
must have had a fine time with Yolanda' — the illusion breaks and the
kid gets suspicious. Cortex only helps when the writer is honest about
what the game actually knows. Do not fake it.

---

## 3.4 Reading past-choices as an alist

For messier stories with lots of small choices, one flag per choice
gets out of hand. Use a single alist called `past-choices`.

```scheme
;; Instead of many separate flags:
(cortex/write 'state/first-door 'red)
(cortex/write 'state/ate-honey? #t)
(cortex/write 'state/spared-wolf? #t)

;; Use one bundle:
(define (remember-choice key value)
  (let ((old (or (cortex/read 'past-choices) '())))
    (cortex/write 'past-choices (cons (cons key value) old))))

(define (recall-choice key)
  (let ((old (or (cortex/read 'past-choices) '())))
    (cdr (or (assoc key old) '(#f . #f)))))

;; Now:
(remember-choice 'first-door 'red)
(remember-choice 'ate-honey? #t)
(remember-choice 'spared-wolf? #t)

(recall-choice 'first-door)   ;; => 'red
(recall-choice 'ate-honey?)   ;; => #t
(recall-choice 'never-set)    ;; => #f
```

Every choice you make in the story flows through
`remember-choice`. Later, any character can `recall-choice` any past
decision. The alist grows without bound, but Cortex handles that; you
do not need to prune it.

This pattern is worth using early. The first time you catch yourself
adding a fourth `cortex/write 'state/...`, migrate to alist-shape and
you will not regret it.

---

## 3.5 Reputation as a number

Sometimes the past is not a boolean but a magnitude. How much does
Mira trust you? Not 'yes' or 'no' — a number.

```scheme
;; Reputation with an NPC as a signed integer.
(define (rep-change npc delta)
  (let* ((key (string->symbol
                (string-append \"reputation/\" (symbol->string npc))))
         (old (or (cortex/read key) 0)))
    (cortex/write key (+ old delta))))

(define (rep npc)
  (let ((key (string->symbol
               (string-append \"reputation/\" (symbol->string npc)))))
    (or (cortex/read key) 0)))

;; The kid does a kind thing:
(rep-change 'mira +2)

;; The kid does a cold thing:
(rep-change 'mira -1)

;; Mira's dialogue branches on it:
(define (mira-greeting)
  (let ((r (rep 'mira)))
    (cond
      ((> r 5)  \"Oh, it is YOU. Come in, sit, tell me everything.\")
      ((> r 0)  \"Hello again. Nice to see you.\")
      ((= r 0)  \"Hello.\")
      (else     \"You. Well. What is it you want.\"))))
```

Every kindness moves the number up. Every coldness moves it down. Mira
greets accordingly. The kid does not know the exact number — she just
feels that Mira warms up over time, or cools down. That is how
reputation works in life. It is also how it works in some of the best
role-playing games.

Reputation lives in Cortex under `reputation/<npc>`. It survives
sessions. The kid closes the game with Mira at rep 7 and opens
tomorrow with Mira still at 7.

---

## 3.6 The 'previously on…' recap

Long narrative games benefit from a recap the way TV shows do. When
the kid opens the game after two days away, remind her.

```scheme
;; Show a two-second recap of the last three big events.
(define (previously-on)
  (scene/imagine)
  (surface/paper)
  (paint-text 20 40 \"~~ previously ~~\")
  (let ((recent (cortex/topk 3)))
    (let loop ((es recent) (i 0))
      (when (not (null? es))
        (paint-text 20 (+ 80 (* i 30)) (event->prose (car es)))
        (loop (cdr es) (+ i 1)))))
  (world/after 180                     ;; three seconds
    (lambda () (start-game))))

(define (event->prose entry)
  ;; entry is a cortex log record — a pair of (key . value) plus a timestamp.
  ;; We render it as a short human sentence.
  (let ((key (car entry))
        (val (cdr entry)))
    (cond
      ((eq? key 'past-choices)
       (string-append \"You chose: \" (symbol->string (car val))))
      ((eq? key 'inventory)
       (string-append \"You picked up: \" (symbol->string (car val))))
      ((string-prefix? \"reputation/\" (symbol->string key))
       (string-append \"You dealt with \"
                      (string-drop (symbol->string key) 11)
                      \".\"))
      (else
       \"…something happened.\"))))
```

Three most recent Cortex writes become three lines of prose recap. The
kid sees 'you chose garden, you picked up tomato, you dealt with mira'
and the story wraps back around her shoulders like a familiar blanket.
Three seconds and then the game continues.

You can go fancier with `ai/summarize` — feed it the last 20 entries
and ask for a two-line prose summary. Chapter 12 covers that. For now,
top-3 with hand-crafted rendering is plenty.

---

## 3.7 A worked scene: three shopkeepers, one kid

The kid has been playing for two hours across three sessions. She has
past-choices: took-red-door, ate-honey, spared-wolf, gave-note-to-mira.
Inventory: tomato, lantern, feather. Reputations: mira +4, villain -2,
kestrel +1.

She walks into a village square. Three shopkeepers. Each greets her
based on what THEY would know.

```scheme
(define (village-square)
  (scene/imagine)
  (surface/paper)
  (paint-text 20 40 \"The square. Three stalls. Three people you know.\")
  (paint-text 20 100 (baker-greeting))
  (paint-text 20 160 (smith-greeting))
  (paint-text 20 220 (herbalist-greeting)))

(define (baker-greeting)
  (cond
    ((> (rep 'mira) 3)
     \"BAKER: 'Oh! Mira sent word ahead. There is a bread for you.'\")
    ((recall-choice 'ate-honey?)
     \"BAKER: 'You are the honey-eater. I have a jar with your name.'\")
    (else
     \"BAKER: 'Morning. Loaves are two coppers.'\")))

(define (smith-greeting)
  (cond
    ((recall-choice 'spared-wolf?)
     \"SMITH: 'I heard about the wolf. That was not a small thing.'\")
    ((recall-choice 'gave-note-to-mira?)
     \"SMITH: 'You brought the note. I owe you a favor.'\")
    (else
     \"SMITH: 'You need an edge sharpened?'\")))

(define (herbalist-greeting)
  (cond
    ((> (rep 'villain) 0)   ;; kid befriended the villain?
     \"HERBALIST: 'You are the one who talks with the wolf. Careful.'\")
    ((< (rep 'villain) -1)
     \"HERBALIST: 'You are the one who stood up to him. Good.'\")
    (else
     \"HERBALIST: 'Fresh mint. Fresh sage. What do you need?'\")))
```

Three greetings, each read from a different corner of Cortex. Nobody
mentions everything — the baker does not know about the wolf, the
smith does not know about the honey. Each shopkeeper knows what a
shopkeeper would know: the baker heard from Mira, the smith heard about
the wolf-and-note, the herbalist has strong opinions about the
villain. This is realism as design: characters know some things, not
all things.

Play this scene four times over four playthroughs and it has four
different textures. The kid never sees the same square twice. The game
did not grow bigger. Cortex just remembered more, and the writers
tapped that.

---

## 3.8 Common desktop tasks — a repeat customer

A shopkeeper's cart. A customer has bought from her twice before. On
the third visit the greeting should be personal.

```scheme
;; Ambient shopkeeper cart — greets a returning customer by history.
(define-card 'shop-personal-greeting
  :init
  (lambda ()
    (let* ((visits    (or (cortex/read 'customer/visits) 0))
           (last-buy  (cortex/read 'customer/last-purchase))
           (fav-color (cortex/read 'customer/fav-color)))
      (cortex/write 'customer/visits (+ visits 1))
      (scene/imagine)
      (surface/paper)
      (paint-text 20 40
        (cond
          ((and last-buy (> visits 2))
           (string-append \"You came back. The \" last-buy
                          \" is treating you well I hope?\"))
          ((= visits 1)
           \"First time in. Welcome.\")
          (else
           \"Welcome back.\")))
      (when fav-color
        (paint-text 20 100
          (string-append \"I set aside a piece in \" fav-color
                         \" — thought of you when it came in.\")))
      (paint-text 20 200 \"[A] browse   [B] special orders\"))))
```

The customer visits for the third time. She bought a cast-iron skillet
last time. Her favorite color, which she once mentioned in chat, was
green. The card greets her: 'you came back — the skillet is treating
you well I hope?' and 'I set aside a piece in green — thought of you
when it came in.'

The customer is a customer. The shopkeeper cannot remember every
detail about every visitor. Cortex CAN. And the operator wrote the
tiny card that lets Cortex whisper the details into her greeting.
This is what turns a shop into a place.

Persistence caveat: `customer/visits` and `customer/fav-color` are
per-customer, so they live in a Cortex scope keyed to the customer id.
Appendix A shows the recommended scoping. For now, know that Cortex
handles per-user isolation for you.

---

## 3.9 Cross-session persistence — the acid test

Here is how you know Cortex is really working across sessions: quit
the game, restart your machine, open the game, and see if it remembers.

```scheme
;; A tiny test — set a value, quit, come back, check it.
(define (test-persistence)
  (scene/imagine)
  (surface/paper)
  (let ((saved (cortex/read 'test/persisted)))
    (if saved
        (begin
          (paint-text 20 40
            (string-append \"Cortex says: \" saved))
          (paint-text 20 80
            \"That value came from a previous session.\"))
        (begin
          (cortex/write 'test/persisted \"a plum tree in blossom\")
          (paint-text 20 40 \"I wrote a plum tree in blossom to Cortex.\")
          (paint-text 20 80 \"Quit and come back. It will still be here.\")))))
```

Run it once. See the write message. Quit. Run it again. See the plum
tree quoted back at you. That is the whole magic. Any string, symbol,
list, or number you write is still there tomorrow. The story remembers.

The kid who understands this understands the difference between a
video game and a narrative game. A video game resets. A narrative game
keeps you.

---

## 3.10 Closing

Cortex is three verbs and a naming convention. Use them well and the
kid's character grows a body. Six characters remember her from
different angles. The shopkeeper says 'I heard from Mira.' The
herbalist has strong opinions about the villain. The baker set aside
a piece in green.

The physics of memory: story gets heavier the longer you play. In a
narrative game with no memory, every scene weighs the same. In one
with Cortex, scene 40 carries scene 3 on its shoulders. That is why
we play.

Chapter 4 gives characters bodies. Right now they are voices in the
dark. Next they will breathe, and lean, and look at you. Cortex knows
who; the body shows who.")
